            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1269778265,
            "creation_date": 1269778265,
            "body": "<p>The value of the <code>elvis<\/code> variable is being captured by the anonymous inner class.<\/p>\n\n<p>Java only (currently) captures variables <em>by value<\/em>. The compiler requires that the variable is final so that there can be no confusion about what will actually be used when the <code>run<\/code> method is called in the new thread: if you changed the value of <code>elvis<\/code> after creating the new thread but before starting it, what would you expect it to do?<\/p>\n\n<p>This is a difference between the way that closures are effectively available in C# and Java. See my <a href=\"http://csharpindepth.com/Articles/Chapter5/Closures.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">closures article<\/a> for more details of this. Java 7 will make closures more concise - I haven't been following along to know whether there will be any way of capturing the variable itself rather than a particular value.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532821,
            "question_id": 2532798
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a4d5888f021e337d09be5b3109c11e72?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 46249,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 136540,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/136540/michael-aaron-safyan",
                "reputation": 96071,
                "display_name": "Michael Aaron Safyan",
                "accept_rate": 83
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269778656,
            "creation_date": 1269778656,
            "body": "<p>This has nothing to do with threads and everything to do with constructing anonymous classes. The issue is that you are referencing a local variable from within the anonymous class. Now consider the following:<\/p>\n\n<pre>\nint c = 5;\nRunnable r = new Runnable(){ public void run(){ System.out.println(c); } };\nc = 6;\nr.run();\n<\/pre>\n\n<p>In the snippet above, should the code print 5 or should it print 6? If r were to hold onto a reference to the current stack frame in order to resolve c, it  is conceivable that it could print 6. It is also conceivable that it could bind/capture the value of c earlier and print a 5. Java forces you to make c final so as to make this completely clear and also to absolve Java of the need to hang onto the current stack frame.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532836,
            "question_id": 2532798
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dd5a7ef1476fb01998a215b1642dfd07?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 19061,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 44330,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/44330/jason-s",
                "reputation": 190586,
                "display_name": "Jason S",
                "accept_rate": 70
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269779362,
            "creation_date": 1269779362,
            "body": "<p>this isn't part of your question but i'm just curious: why are you reassigning Elvis.x if it's an AtomicInteger? that kind of misses the point of AtomicInteger's thread-safety. Consider rewriting:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public Elvis {\n\n   final static private Elvis INSTANCE = new Elvis(2);\n   static public Elvis getInstance() { return INSTANCE; }\n\n   final private AtomicInteger x; \n\n\n   Elvis() { this(0); }\n\n   Elvis(int x){ \n      this.x = new AtomicInteger(x);\n   }\n\n   public int getX() { return this.x.get(); }\n\n   public void setX(int x) {this.x.set(x); }\n\n   public void sing(int x) {\n      setX(x);\n      System.out.println(\"Elvis singing..\" + x);\n   }\n }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>also since this has mutable content, it shouldn't be an enum.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532873,
            "question_id": 2532798
        }
